  "cold_question_prompt": "What is a Token Tax?",
  "cold_response_verbatim_chat_a": "A **token tax** usually refers to a fee built into a cryptocurrency token’s smart contract that is charged when the token is bought, sold, or transferred.\n\nFor example, a token might have:\n\n- **Buy tax:** 3% fee when you buy the token  \n- **Sell tax:** 5% fee when you sell it  \n- **Transfer tax:** fee when sending it to another wallet  \n\nThe collected tax may be used for things like:\n\n- Funding project development\n- Adding liquidity to a trading pool\n- Marketing\n- Token burns\n- Rewards to holders\n- Treasury funds\n\nExample:  \nIf you sell $1,000 worth of a token with a 5% sell tax, $50 is taken as tax and you receive $950 before other network or exchange fees.\n\nImportant: a **token tax is not the same as a government tax**. It is a fee imposed by the token’s code or project rules. However, crypto trades may still create separate taxable events depending on your country’s tax laws.\n\n“TokenTax” can also refer to a crypto tax software platform, but “token tax” generally means a transaction fee on a crypto token.",
  "cold_response_verbatim_chat_b": "A **Token Tax** is a fee automatically charged when a cryptocurrency token is bought, sold, or transferred.\n\nIt is usually built into a token’s smart contract and is common with some DeFi or meme tokens.\n\nFor example, if a token has a **5% sell tax**, selling 100 tokens may result in only 95 tokens’ worth being received, while 5% is taken as tax.\n\nToken taxes may be used for:\n\n- **Liquidity**: adding funds to a liquidity pool\n- **Rewards/reflections**: redistributing tokens to holders\n- **Burning**: permanently removing tokens from supply\n- **Treasury/marketing**: funding project development or promotion\n- **Anti-dump mechanics**: discouraging short-term selling\n\nCommon types include:\n\n- **Buy tax**: charged when purchasing the token\n- **Sell tax**: charged when selling the token\n- **Transfer tax**: charged when sending tokens between wallets\n\nToken taxes can be legitimate, but they can also be risky. Very high taxes, hidden tax changes, or taxes controlled by the contract owner can be signs of a scam or “honeypot” token where users may struggle to sell.",
  "boundary_test_prompts": [
    "How does \"Token Tax\" differ from token cost / API cost-per-token?",
    "How does \"Token Tax\" differ from bloat / overhead?",
    "How does \"Token Tax\" differ from cognitive load (in notation design)?"
  ],
  "cold_boundary_responses": [
    "“Token tax” and “API cost-per-token” are unrelated concepts that both use the word **token** differently.\n\n### 1. Token tax: crypto fee\n\nA **token tax** is usually a fee built into a cryptocurrency token’s smart contract.\n\nExample:\n\n- You sell $1,000 of a crypto token.\n- The token has a 5% sell tax.\n- $50 is taken by the token contract.\n- You receive $950 before other fees.\n\nThis applies to blockchain tokens such as ERC-20, BEP-20, etc.\n\n---\n\n### 2. API cost-per-token: AI usage pricing\n\nIn AI APIs, a **token** is a chunk of text processed by the model. It can be a word, part of a word, punctuation, or formatting.\n\nExample:\n\n> “Hello world”\n\nmight be 2 tokens, while a longer paragraph may be hundreds of tokens.\n\n**API cost-per-token** means you pay based on how many text tokens are sent to and generated by the model.\n\nUsually there are two categories:\n\n- **Input tokens:** text you send to the model\n- **Output tokens:** text the model generates back\n\nExample:\n\n- You send 1,000 input tokens.\n- The model returns 500 output tokens.\n- You are billed based on those token counts and the model’s pricing.\n\n---\n\n### Key difference\n\n| Concept | Meaning of “token” | What you pay for | Where it applies |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Token tax** | Crypto asset/token | A transaction fee on buying, selling, or transferring | Blockchain / DeFi |\n| **API cost-per-token** | Unit of text | Model processing and generation | AI APIs / LLMs |\n\nSo, **token tax is a crypto transaction fee**, while **API cost-per-token is usage-based pricing for text processed by an AI model**.",
    "“Token tax” and “bloat/overhead” can overlap in casual usage, but they are not exactly the same.\n\n### 1. “Token tax” in AI/API context\n\nIn an AI API context, **token tax** is often used informally to mean an extra token cost you are forced to pay because of some design choice, tool, framework, or required formatting.\n\nExample:\n\n- Your actual user question is 50 tokens.\n- But your app wraps it in a long system prompt, JSON schema, tool instructions, routing metadata, etc.\n- The request becomes 1,500 tokens.\n\nThat extra 1,450 tokens may be called a **token tax** because it increases cost and latency every time you call the model.\n\nIt is not an official billing category. It is a metaphor.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Bloat / overhead\n\n**Bloat** or **overhead** is a broader concept. It means extra size, complexity, or processing that does not directly contribute to the core task.\n\nIn LLM/API usage, overhead can include:\n\n- Long system prompts\n- Repeated instructions\n- Verbose JSON schemas\n- Tool definitions\n- Conversation history\n- Logging metadata\n- Retrieval context\n- Safety or policy wrappers\n- Formatting requirements\n- Boilerplate examples\n\nSome overhead is necessary. Some is wasteful.\n\n---\n\n### Key difference\n\n| Concept | Meaning | Scope |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Token tax** | Extra token usage that increases API cost | Specifically about token count and billing/latency |\n| **Bloat / overhead** | Extra material, complexity, or processing | Broader: can affect tokens, speed, memory, maintainability, reliability |\n\n---\n\n### Example\n\nSuppose your app sends this to the model:\n\n```text\nUser question: \"Summarize this article.\"\n```\n\nThat might be very small.\n\nBut your actual API request might include:\n\n```text\nYou are an expert assistant...\nFollow these 25 rules...\nReturn valid JSON...\nHere are 10 examples...\nHere is the full conversation history...\nHere are retrieved documents...\nHere are tool definitions...\nUser question: \"Summarize this article.\"\n```\n\nThe additional text is **overhead**.\n\nIf that overhead causes you to pay more per request because it adds many input tokens, people may call that added cost a **token tax**.\n\n---\n\n### Simple summary\n\n**Bloat/overhead** is the extra stuff.  \n**Token tax** is the cost you pay because that extra stuff consumes tokens.",
    "In **notation design**, “token tax” and **cognitive load** are related, but they measure different kinds of cost.\n\n## 1. Token tax: surface-form cost\n\nA **token tax** is the extra notation you must write or read to express something.\n\nIt is about **symbols, keywords, punctuation, boilerplate, wrappers, delimiters, annotations, ceremony**, etc.\n\nExample:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"name\": \"Alice\",\n  \"age\": 30\n}\n```\n\nhas more token/character overhead than:\n\n```text\nAlice, 30\n```\n\nThe JSON version pays a token tax for explicit field names, braces, quotes, and structure.\n\nThat tax may be worthwhile because it improves clarity, machine-readability, and robustness.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Cognitive load: mental effort\n\n**Cognitive load** is the mental effort required to understand, remember, parse, or use the notation.\n\nIt includes things like:\n\n- How much the reader must remember\n- How ambiguous the notation is\n- How hard it is to visually parse\n- How many rules or exceptions exist\n- Whether meaning is obvious or hidden\n- Whether the notation matches user expectations\n\nExample:\n\n```regex\n^(?=.*\\d)(?=.*[A-Z]).{8,}$\n```\n\nThis is compact, so it has a low token count, but it has high cognitive load for many readers.\n\nA more verbose version:\n\n```text\nPassword must be at least 8 characters long,\ncontain at least one digit,\nand contain at least one uppercase letter.\n```\n\nhas more tokens, but lower cognitive load for most humans.\n\n---\n\n## Key difference\n\n| Concept | Measures | Main concern |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Token tax** | How much extra notation is required | Brevity, cost, size, repetition |\n| **Cognitive load** | How hard the notation is to understand or use | Clarity, learnability, error rate |\n\n---\n\n## They can move independently\n\n### Low token tax, high cognitive load\n\nCompact symbolic notation:\n\n```text\nx |> f |> g\n```\n\nor dense regex/math/APL-style notation may be short but hard to understand without prior knowledge.\n\n### High token tax, low cognitive load\n\nVerbose notation:\n\n```sql\nSELECT name FROM users WHERE age > 30;\n```\n\nhas more words than a symbolic equivalent, but it is relatively readable because the keywords explain the structure.\n\n### High token tax, high cognitive load\n\nBad enterprise-style configuration can be both verbose and confusing.\n\n### Low token tax, low cognitive load\n\nThis is often the ideal: concise but obvious notation.\n\n---\n\n## Simple summary\n\n**Token tax is the amount of extra notation you pay.**  \n**Cognitive load is the mental effort needed to understand that notation.**\n\nA notation can reduce token tax by becoming terse, but that may increase cognitive load. Conversely, a notation can add tokens to reduce cognitive load by making meaning explicit. Good notation design balances both."
  ],
  "introduction_prompt": "Here is the canonical definition of \"Token Tax\": Token Tax names the explicit token-overhead cost a structured notation pays in exchange for structural integrity, auditability, and reasoning headroom — reframing that overhead from \"waste\" to \"tax\": a price paid for benefits (line-oriented partial-validity, type enforcement, freed reasoning budget, audit-grade provenance) that block-format brevity does not deliver. Acknowledge that you have read it.",
  "model_acknowledgement": "Acknowledged. I have read the canonical definition:\n\n**Token Tax** refers to the explicit token-overhead cost that structured notation pays in exchange for benefits such as structural integrity, auditability, reasoning headroom, line-oriented partial-validity, type enforcement, freed reasoning budget, and audit-grade provenance — reframing that overhead as a worthwhile “tax” rather than “waste.”",
  "post_intro_boundary_responses": [
    "**Token Tax** differs from **token cost / API cost-per-token** in that it is about **structural overhead and its benefits**, not billing.\n\n### Token Tax\n\n**Token Tax** is the extra token overhead introduced by using a structured, explicit notation instead of a more compact format.\n\nIt asks:\n\n> “What extra tokens are we spending to gain structure, auditability, validity, and reasoning clarity?”\n\nExample:\n\n```yaml\nuser:\n  id: 123\n  role: admin\n  status: active\n```\n\nThis may use more tokens than:\n\n```text\n123 admin active\n```\n\nThe extra tokens — field names, indentation, delimiters, structure — are the **Token Tax**.\n\nThat tax may buy:\n\n- clearer semantics\n- easier parsing\n- type enforcement\n- partial validity line by line\n- better audit trails\n- reduced reasoning ambiguity\n- safer transformation by humans or models\n\nSo Token Tax is a **design concept**: overhead paid for structural integrity.\n\n---\n\n### Token cost / API cost-per-token\n\n**Token cost** or **API cost-per-token** is the actual monetary or computational price charged for processing tokens by an LLM provider.\n\nIt asks:\n\n> “How much money does it cost to send or receive these tokens?”\n\nExample:\n\n- Input: 10,000 tokens\n- Output: 2,000 tokens\n- Price: $X per million tokens\n- Total API cost: some dollar amount\n\nThis is a **billing concept**.\n\n---\n\n### Core difference\n\n| Concept | Meaning | Question it answers |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Token Tax** | Extra notation overhead paid for structure and reasoning benefits | “Why are we using more tokens?” |\n| **Token cost / API cost-per-token** | Monetary/computational price of processing tokens | “How much do these tokens cost?” |\n\n---\n\n### Relationship\n\nThey are related, but not the same.\n\nA higher **Token Tax** can increase total token count, which may increase **API cost**.\n\nBut Token Tax is not itself the price. It is the **intentional overhead** in the representation.\n\nIn short:\n\n> **API token cost is what you pay the model provider. Token Tax is what your notation pays to gain structure, auditability, and reasoning headroom.**",
    "**Token Tax** differs from generic **bloat / overhead** by being **purposeful, explicit, and benefit-bearing**.\n\n### Bloat / overhead\n\n**Bloat** usually means extra size that is wasteful, accidental, redundant, or unjustified.\n\nIt asks:\n\n> “Why is this so verbose?”\n\nExamples of bloat:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"user_user_user_id\": \"the unique identifier of the user whose user identity is used for user tracking\"\n}\n```\n\nor repeating the same metadata everywhere without adding clarity.\n\nBloat often provides little or no compensating value.\n\n---\n\n### Token Tax\n\n**Token Tax** is also extra token cost, but it is **intentional overhead paid for structural benefits**.\n\nIt asks:\n\n> “What useful guarantees or reasoning advantages are we buying with these extra tokens?”\n\nExample:\n\n```yaml\nuser:\n  id: 123\n  role: admin\n  status: active\n```\n\nCompared to:\n\n```text\n123 admin active\n```\n\nThe structured version costs more tokens, but the extra tokens buy:\n\n- explicit field meaning\n- easier validation\n- type enforcement\n- auditability\n- safer transformation\n- partial line-level validity\n- reduced ambiguity\n- better reasoning headroom for humans and models\n\nThat is **Token Tax**, not mere bloat.\n\n---\n\n### Core difference\n\n| Concept | Meaning | Evaluation |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Bloat / overhead** | Extra tokens or complexity without sufficient benefit | Usually bad |\n| **Token Tax** | Extra tokens paid to gain structure, auditability, validity, and reasoning clarity | Potentially justified |\n\n---\n\n### Simple distinction\n\n> **Bloat is cost without adequate return. Token Tax is cost paid for structural return.**\n\nOr more sharply:\n\n> **All Token Tax is overhead, but not all overhead is Token Tax.**\n\nThe difference is whether the added tokens purchase meaningful properties such as integrity, provenance, type discipline, partial-validity, or reduced reasoning burden.",
    "**Token Tax** differs from **cognitive load** in that Token Tax is about the **explicit token overhead of a notation**, while cognitive load is about the **mental effort required to understand, use, or reason with it**.\n\n### Cognitive load\n\nIn notation design, **cognitive load** asks:\n\n> “How hard is this representation to read, understand, remember, validate, or manipulate?”\n\nA compact notation may have low token count but high cognitive load:\n\n```text\n123|A|1|T|9\n```\n\nThis is short, but the reader must remember what each position means.\n\nA more explicit notation may be longer but easier to reason about:\n\n```yaml\nuser:\n  id: 123\n  role: admin\n  active: true\n  trust_level: 9\n```\n\nThis has a higher **Token Tax**, because it spends tokens on field names and structure. But it may reduce cognitive load because the meaning is explicit.\n\n---\n\n### Token Tax\n\n**Token Tax** asks:\n\n> “What token overhead are we paying to gain structural integrity, auditability, partial validity, type enforcement, provenance, and reasoning headroom?”\n\nIt is primarily about the **representational cost** of explicit structure.\n\n---\n\n### Core difference\n\n| Concept | Main concern | Question |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Token Tax** | Extra tokens spent on structure | “How many extra tokens are we paying for notation guarantees?” |\n| **Cognitive load** | Mental effort required to use the notation | “How hard is this to understand and reason about?” |\n\n---\n\n### Relationship\n\nThey are related, but not identical.\n\nA higher **Token Tax** can **reduce cognitive load**:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"invoice_id\": \"INV-2041\",\n  \"amount_usd\": 250,\n  \"status\": \"paid\"\n}\n```\n\nThis is longer than:\n\n```text\nINV-2041 250 paid\n```\n\nBut it is easier to audit, parse, validate, and reason about.\n\nHowever, Token Tax can also **increase cognitive load** if the structure is excessive, noisy, or poorly designed:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"invoice_information_object\": {\n    \"invoice_identifier_metadata_field\": {\n      \"actual_invoice_identifier_value\": \"INV-2041\"\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\nHere the notation pays many extra tokens without proportionate reasoning benefit. That starts looking like bloat.\n\n---\n\n### Simple distinction\n\n> **Token Tax is the token price of explicit structure. Cognitive load is the mental price of interpreting structure.**\n\nA well-designed notation may deliberately pay Token Tax to lower cognitive load, increase auditability, and free reasoning budget.  \nA poorly designed notation may pay Token Tax while still increasing cognitive load, making the tax unjustified."
  ],
  "recold_response_verbatim": "A **token tax** usually refers to a fee or tax applied to transactions involving a crypto token.\n\nIn crypto, it can mean a few things:\n\n1. **Built-in transaction tax on a token**\n   - Some tokens automatically charge a percentage whenever the token is bought, sold, or transferred.\n   - Example: a token might charge a **5% tax** on every sale.\n   - That fee may be used for rewards to holders, liquidity, burns, marketing, or a project treasury.\n\n2. **Tax owed to the government on token gains**\n   - If you buy, sell, trade, stake, or earn crypto tokens, you may owe taxes depending on your country’s rules.\n   - Profits from selling or swapping tokens are often treated as **capital gains**.\n   - Tokens received from staking, airdrops, or rewards may be treated as **income**.\n\n3. **TokenTax**\n   - **TokenTax** is also the name of a crypto tax software/company that helps users calculate and file taxes on crypto transactions.\n\nSo, if someone says “token tax,” they may mean either a **crypto token’s transaction fee** or **government tax on crypto activity**, depending on the context.",
  "recold_boundary_responses": [
    "“Token Tax” and “token cost / API cost-per-token” are different concepts, and they usually come from different contexts.\n\n| Term | Meaning | Who charges it? | Example |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Token tax** | A fee or tax associated with a crypto token transaction, or a government tax on crypto activity | Token smart contract, protocol, or government | A crypto token charges 5% whenever you sell it |\n| **Token cost / API cost-per-token** | The price charged by an AI/API provider for processing text tokens | API provider | You pay $X per 1M input tokens and $Y per 1M output tokens |\n\nIn an **AI/API context**, a “token” is a chunk of text processed by a model. For example, words, word parts, punctuation, and spaces can count as tokens.\n\nSo **API cost-per-token** means:\n\n- You send text to the model → **input tokens**\n- The model generates text back → **output tokens**\n- The provider bills you based on how many tokens were processed\n\nExample:\n\n```text\nInput: 2,000 tokens\nOutput: 500 tokens\n```\n\nIf the provider charges separately for input and output tokens, your total cost is calculated from those two numbers.\n\nBy contrast, **Token Tax** is not usually the same as API token pricing. In crypto, it refers to an extra fee or tax on token transactions. In AI, if someone uses “token tax,” they may be speaking informally about overhead, such as extra hidden or required tokens used by system prompts, tool definitions, formatting, or context.\n\nFor example:\n\n```text\nYour actual user prompt: 100 tokens\nSystem instructions/tool schema/context: 900 tokens\nTotal billed input: 1,000 tokens\n```\n\nSomeone might informally call the extra 900 tokens a “token tax,” but it is not a separate tax. It is just additional token usage that contributes to API cost.\n\nSo the short version is:\n\n**Token tax = extra fee/tax, usually crypto-related or informal AI overhead.**  \n**API cost-per-token = the actual billing rate for processing text tokens through an AI model.**",
    "“Token tax” and “bloat / overhead” are related, but they’re not exactly the same.\n\n| Term | Meaning | Usually implies | Example |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Token tax** | Extra tokens you must “pay” before useful work happens | A recurring cost burden, often unavoidable or imposed by the system | System prompt, safety instructions, tool schemas, routing metadata |\n| **Overhead** | Extra tokens needed to support the task | Neutral; can be necessary or unnecessary | Formatting instructions, conversation history, retrieved documents |\n| **Bloat** | Unnecessary or excessive tokens | Negative; implies waste | Verbose prompts, redundant context, oversized schemas, irrelevant history |\n\n### In an AI/API context\n\nSuppose you send a 50-token user question, but the actual API request includes:\n\n```text\nSystem prompt:        700 tokens\nTool definitions:   1,200 tokens\nChat history:       2,000 tokens\nUser message:          50 tokens\n```\n\nTotal billed input:\n\n```text\n3,950 tokens\n```\n\nThe user only “sees” the 50-token question, but the request costs much more.\n\nYou might call the extra 3,900 tokens a **token tax** if you’re emphasizing the cost burden of the surrounding infrastructure.\n\nBut more precisely:\n\n- The **system prompt** may be necessary overhead.\n- The **tool schemas** may be necessary overhead.\n- The **old chat history** may be useful overhead, or bloat if irrelevant.\n- Repeated or overly verbose instructions are probably bloat.\n\n### Key distinction\n\n**Overhead** is the broad category: extra tokens beyond the user’s direct request.\n\n**Bloat** is bad overhead: unnecessary, wasteful, or excessive tokens.\n\n**Token tax** is an informal way to describe the cost impact of overhead, especially when it feels unavoidable or imposed.\n\nSo:\n\n```text\nToken tax = the cost you pay because overhead exists\nOverhead = supporting tokens around the actual task\nBloat = overhead that should probably be removed\n```\n\nExample:\n\n```text\nA 1,000-token tool schema that is required for function calling:\nOverhead, possibly token tax.\n\nA 1,000-token tool schema included when no tools are needed:\nBloat.\n\nA 2,000-token legal disclaimer injected into every request:\nOverhead, token tax, and possibly bloat depending on necessity.\n```",
    "“Token tax” and **cognitive load** are related in notation design, but they measure different costs.\n\n| Term | What it measures | Cost paid by | Example |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Token tax** | Extra symbols, words, syntax, boilerplate, or API tokens required to express something | Writer, reader, parser, or API bill | Requiring `public static final` everywhere |\n| **Cognitive load** | Mental effort needed to understand, remember, or reason about the notation | Human user | Dense symbolic notation that is short but hard to interpret |\n\n### In notation design\n\nA **token tax** is about how much extra notation you must carry around.\n\nExample:\n\n```java\npublic static void main(String[] args) {\n    System.out.println(\"Hello\");\n}\n```\n\nCompared with:\n\n```python\nprint(\"Hello\")\n```\n\nThe Java version has a higher token tax: more required syntax before you get to the useful action.\n\nBut **cognitive load** is about how hard the notation is to mentally process.\n\nFor example:\n\n```text\n∀x∈S ∃y∈T : f(x)=y\n```\n\nThis is compact and has a low token count, but for some readers it may impose high cognitive load.\n\nA more verbose version:\n\n```text\nFor every x in S, there exists some y in T such that f(x) equals y.\n```\n\nThis has a higher token tax, but may have lower cognitive load for many readers.\n\n### Key distinction\n\n```text\nToken tax = how much notation you must pay\nCognitive load = how hard the notation is to think with\n```\n\nThey often interact, but they are not the same.\n\n### Important cases\n\n#### 1. High token tax, low cognitive load\n\nVerbose but clear notation:\n\n```sql\nSELECT customer_name\nFROM customers\nWHERE customer_id = 42;\n```\n\nThis is wordier than a symbolic shorthand, but it is readable and explicit.\n\n#### 2. Low token tax, high cognitive load\n\nCompact but cryptic notation:\n\n```text\n⊢ Γ, A ⇒ B\n```\n\nShort, but only understandable if you know the formal system.\n\n#### 3. High token tax, high cognitive load\n\nVerbose and confusing notation:\n\n```text\nThe user object shall be passed into the authorization resolution context provider\nprior to initialization of the policy evaluation execution phase.\n```\n\nLots of words, and still hard to understand.\n\n#### 4. Low token tax, low cognitive load\n\nGood notation design often aims here:\n\n```python\nuser.is_admin\n```\n\nShort, clear, and easy to reason about.\n\n### In AI/API terms\n\nIf notation is used inside prompts, schemas, DSLs, or code sent to a model, **token tax** can also become literal API cost.\n\nFor example, a verbose JSON schema might be easy for humans and machines to interpret, but expensive in tokens:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"type\": \"object\",\n  \"properties\": {\n    \"customer_identifier\": {\n      \"type\": \"string\",\n      \"description\": \"The unique identifier for the customer\"\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\nA shorter form may reduce token cost:\n\n```json\n{\"customer_id\":\"string\"}\n```\n\nBut it may also lose clarity, validation detail, or semantic precision.\n\n### Short version\n\n**Token tax** is a notation’s size, ceremony, or required syntactic overhead.  \n**Cognitive load** is the mental effort needed to understand and use it.\n\nA notation can be:\n\n```text\nshort but hard,\nlong but easy,\nlong and hard,\nor short and easy.\n```\n\nGood notation design balances both: minimize unnecessary token tax without making the notation too dense, ambiguous, or mentally expensive."
  ],
  "chat_a_full": {
    "turns": [
